		{"id":"a009fc2a723584d0","type":"text","text":"Absolutely. Here's a **character-centered scene** focused entirely on Mr. Gribble, capturing his world and personality just before the Glowling enters his life. This can serve as an **opening vignette** or a standalone backstory moment for your _BlackBook Tales_ episode.\n\n---\n\n## üé¨ **Scene: ‚ÄúGribble‚Äôs Clockwork Silence‚Äù**\n\n**Setting**: Late afternoon. Inside Gribble‚Äôs cluttered, creaking house.  \n**Mood**: Quiet, dusty, laced with faded wonder and slow sadness.\n\n---\n\n### **NARRATION** _(soft, observational)_\n\n> ‚ÄúEvery town has that one house.  \n> The one with no kids, no laughter ‚Äî just the smell of oil, and the sound of ticking things that shouldn‚Äôt tick anymore.  \n> This is Gribble‚Äôs house.‚Äù\n\n---\n\n### **[VISUAL: INT. GRIBBLE'S WORKSHOP ‚Äì DAY]**\n\n- The room is dimly lit by a green-shaded desk lamp. Dust floats like snowflakes in golden shafts of light from a cracked window.\n    \n- The shelves are packed with half-finished inventions:\n    \n    - A bird made of spoons flutters its metal wings.\n        \n    - A one-eyed teddy bear jerks slightly every few minutes, then freezes again.\n        \n    - A wind-up ballerina twitches mid-spin.\n        \n- Gribble sits hunched at a bench. His glasses sit low on his nose as he delicately rewires a tiny robot‚Äôs jaw hinge.\n    \n\n---\n\n### **DIALOGUE (GRIBBLE, muttering to himself)**\n\n> ‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt need a smile, Buzzy... You need tension in the springs. Happiness is mechanical ‚Äî that‚Äôs the trick.‚Äù\n\n- He finishes soldering a circuit. The toy clicks. Its mouth opens... then sparks. Smoke rises. Gribble doesn‚Äôt even flinch.\n    \n\n> _(sighing)_ ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs what I get for trusting a Canadian capacitor‚Ä¶‚Äù\n\n---\n\n### **[VISUAL: WIDER SHOT]**\n\n- The camera pans across the room:\n    \n    - A cracked photo frame: Gribble as a young man, standing proudly next to a giant animatronic dragon.\n        \n    - A wall calendar frozen on **March 1989**.\n        \n    - A tea kettle whistling, but he doesn‚Äôt get up.\n        \n\n---\n\n### **NARRATION (CONT'D)**\n\n> ‚ÄúOnce, Gribble made joy for a living.  \n> Now he makes sparks... and mutters... and talks to things that don‚Äôt talk back.‚Äù\n\n---\n\n### **[VISUAL: GRIBBLE STANDS]**\n\n- He moves to the window.\n    \n- Outside, the yard is filled with rusted toy limbs and crumbling prototypes.\n    \n- He watches a neighborhood kid throw a paper plane. It sails, loops... then crashes.\n    \n\n> _(grumbling)_ ‚ÄúShould‚Äôve added a counterweight to the nose.‚Äù\n\n- He smirks ‚Äî the first hint of life in his face. It fades quickly.\n    \n\n---\n\n### **NARRATION (ENDING)**\n\n> ‚ÄúGribble didn‚Äôt believe in magic.  \n> He believed in tension springs, well-oiled gears, and regret.\n> \n> But the sky was already changing.\n> \n> And soon... the light would find him.‚Äù\n\n---\n\nWould you like this converted into a **script-ready format** for voiceover or adapted into a **motion storyboard layout** with camera notes?","x":-2600,"y":-1644,"width":250,"height":240},
